The network consists of nodes, apps, and all the plumbing to glue it all together.

Apps make requests (relays) to nodes which query the underlying blockchain and relay the data back to the apps.

For their work, nodes are rewarded with POKT.

It is pretty much impossible to buy the token in size now, so you have a week until the launch of the app and liquidity mining programme, enough for in-depth research.

14/ It feels like the AMM model has been around forever, but we're still in the first inning.

Let's see where this next wave of liquidity provisioning management takes us.

13/ Finally, liquidity-management-as-a-platform has the potential to commoditize AMMs. 

Lixir's model should be cleanly portable to other chains, and it's a near certainty that Uni-V3 clones will see this integration as useful.

12/ There is still a ton to explore in this space, particularly around governance. Will V3 pools on platforms like Lixir be permissionless, or will governance take on new importance in allowing projects? It's going to be very interesting to see what comes out of this new setup.
11/ This story is standard in software: new, more powerful products are created, and powerful platforms evolve on top of them to unlock their full functionality.

10/ Lixir will enable exactly this: projects that have pools on Lixir will be able to offer high and optimized APYs on Uni-V3, while configuring parameters for how rewards should be given and in which ranges.

All with the push of a button.

9/ Another way to think of this is that liquidity providers are a resource to be competed for, and projects will need to offer them the best terms, not just with native token APYs, but with optimal liquidity ranges.
7/ However, projects will still want easy ways to incentivize mining their particular pools, and it's here that I think Lixir will really shine as a platform and differentiate itself.

6/ In the first phase of these managers, the differentiator will be the competence of the rebalancing and repricing strategies. I expect the early leaders like Lixir to move quickly here and extend their leads on the market.
5/ Most projects in this space so far are just simple NFT vaults, but there are a couple that are attempting sophisticated re-balancing and allocation strategies.
4/ The first, obvious part of this new approach is managing liquidity concentration. Anyone has played with Uni-V3 knows how active you have to be in order to approach the theoretical ROIs possible.

3/ I call it a "hack" because while its goal was to incentivize liquidity for a given token, the actual fees on Uni-V2 were low enough that extra native rewards had to be added on to give any kind of useful ROI.

Now that you can make real fees on Uni-V3, a new approach is needed

2/ I start by noting that liquidity mining was a slightly unsustainable hack that achieved its goal of bootstrapping the DeFi ecosystem, but can be re-thought now that we have liquidity concentration.

1/ I‚Äôm intrigued by the value-add of Uni-V3 liquidity managers. $LIX (@lixirfinance) in particular seems ambitious enough to be an entire platform, not just a keeper.

The "load-bearing" points of DeFi are changing, and this competes with old-school inflationary rewards.

Please, note, that I'm using the blockchain's size to track our progress as the block number is pretty useless here.

The speed of syncing boils down to the amount of transactions geth needs to process and earlier blocks have very few of them.

Naturally, I expect the sync to be much faster that the last year attempt.

I will update this thread daily until it's done.

Probably, this thread will be of some interest to @peter_szilagyi as well.

We will be using the latest version of Geth and our node is going to be full but non-archive.

That means it's going to be executing all transactions of every block starting from the genesis but it won't be saving all the intermediate states:

geth --syncmode=full --cache=65536

It will cost $190 for the first month and ~$100 monthly thereafter.

Which is actually less than my previous set-up on Digital Ocean. By the way, DO has implemented NVMe storages as well but the cost is prohibitive and Hetzner is more performant anyways.

https://t.co/PoAcqxZwWP

I've decided to up my game a bit and use a much recommended NMVe SSD storage coupled with a powerful CPU and a plenty of RAM.

However, we still need to stay on budget to properly answer the question if an Ethereum full node can be set up and maintained rather cheaply.
